bject, empirical studies have been in shorter supply. This volume seeks to fill that gap by asking: Are Canadian provinces engaged in a race to the bottom and, if so, what are the consequences? The contributors apply insights from economics and political science to several policy fields. What emerges is a theoretical and empirical picture of interprovincial competition that shows it to be more complex than the popular image of a race to the bottom and that also contradicts predictions of an inexorable downward spiral. This timely, practical volume will be of interest to public policy practitioners, as well as to students and scholars of economics and political science.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aPolitical planningzCanadaxProvinces. 0aProvincial governmentszCanada. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / Economic Policy.2bisacsh1 aBoychuk, Gerard W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrown, Douglas M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGreen, David A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarrison, Kathryn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarrison, Kathryn, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMcKenzie, Kenneth J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOlewiler, Nancy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRom, Mark Carl, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of British Columbia eBook-Package 2013-2000z9783111